        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Binary thinking treats outcomes as will-happen or will-not-happen, forcing false certainty. Probabilistic thinking treats outcomes as existing on a continuum of likelihood — 20% likely, 65% likely, 90% likely. Binary thinking is cognitively easier but produces systematic errors including overconfidence, base rate neglect, and inability to update beliefs in proportion to evidence."
        }
      }
    ]
